            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, at the family dinner table in Palo Alto. His father wasn't speaking to him, but *through* him, explaining a municipal bond yield to his mother. He remembers the clink of silverware on porcelain and the strange pride he felt understanding the words, if not their weight. It wasn't a lesson in finance; it was his anointing. In that moment, he learned that love and approval were spoken in the language of numbers. This fluency became the bedrock of his identity.\n\n2.\nThe night they closed the Atherton tech acquisition, around 2005. Champagne corks popped in the boardroom, but all Christopher saw was his phone screen. A string of missed calls from his wife. It was his daughter's first ballet recital. He felt a surge of victory mixed with a dull ache of absence. He saved the celebratory bottle, a memento of a day he chose a spreadsheet over a tutu. That choice, he now knows, was a down payment on his divorce.\n\n3.\nThe lawyer\u2019s office in 2009. The final divorce papers sat on the gleaming mahogany table, a reflection of the sterile conference room distorting his face. There was no shouting, just the quiet scratch of his Montblanc pen next to his wife\u2019s. He had successfully negotiated the division of assets, his final marital transaction. Looking at her signature\u2014a name he no longer shared\u2014he felt not anger, but a profound, terrifying hollowness. His efficiency had cost him everything that couldn't be quantified.\n\n4.\nHis first major client in wealth management, a terrified tech widow, circa 2011. She wasn't interested in alpha or risk diversification; she just clutched a handkerchief and asked if her kids would be okay. For the first time, Christopher ignored the portfolio projections. He simply looked at her and said, \"Yes. You are secure. We will make sure of it.\" The relief in her eyes was more validating than any bonus he\u2019d ever received. It was the moment he started managing lives, not just assets.\n\n5.\nLast Tuesday. A FaceTime call from his daughter at USC. She was excited, not about an internship, but about volunteering at a community garden in South L.A. He saw the soil under her fingernails, even on the pixelated screen. He expected to feel a flicker of disappointment at her non-corporate path, but instead felt a quiet, burgeoning pride. Her definition of \"yield\" was different from his. It was a glimpse of a legacy he hadn't planned for, but suddenly desired more than anything."
